Introduction

In this notebook, I am going to perform differential gene expression analysis and overrepresentation analysis on noramlized data from assignment 1. The original data is RNAseq raw counts. The controls are MCF7 cells transfected with control siRNA and the tests are MCF7 cells transfected with ESR1 siRNAs (SmartPool) and RECQ1 siRNAs (SmartPool) for 48 hours (Lu et al. 2021). In the original paper, they perform gene expression analysis and overrepresentation analysis on ESR1 vs control and RECQ1 vs control to study relation between RECQ1 and ESR1. Also, they are interested in finding relation between RECQ1 and breast cancer.

# Read data from assignment 1

normalized_count_data_path <- "./final_counts.csv"

# Please modify the datapath
normalized_count_data <- read.table(normalized_count_data_path, 
                                    header = TRUE, 
                                    sep = ",", 
                                    stringsAsFactors = FALSE, 
                                    check.names = FALSE)

# Find missing column names for hgnc_symbol
colnames(normalized_count_data)[1] <- "hgnc_symbol"

# Make a martix from normalized data
data_matrix <- normalized_count_data[3: ncol(normalized_count_data)]
rownames(data_matrix) <- normalized_count_data$hgnc_symbol
colnames(data_matrix) <- colnames(normalized_count_data[3: ncol(normalized_count_data)])
# Group them based on different cell types
cell_type <- unlist(strsplit(colnames(normalized_count_data[3: ncol(normalized_count_data)]), "_"))[c(FALSE, TRUE, FALSE)]
samples <- data.frame(cell_type = cell_type)
rownames(samples) <- colnames(normalized_count_data[3: ncol(normalized_count_data)])
# Define model
classes <- samples$cell_type
model_design <- model.matrix(~0 + classes )

Differential Gene Expression

In the original paper, author conducts two differential Gene Expression analysis, one is RecQ1 vs CTL, the other is ESR1 vs CTL. Here, I am going to conduct these two differential Gene Expression analysis. I use Quasi liklihood model for differential expression analysis since it is recommended for bulk rna-seq data and my data is in negative bionomial distribution.

contrast_RecQ1CTL <- makeContrasts(
  RecQ1CTL ="classessiRecQ1-classessiCTL",
  levels=model_design)

contrast_ESR1 <- makeContrasts(
  ESR1CTL ="classessiESR1-classessiCTL",
  levels=model_design)

Differential Gene Expression between RecQ1 knockdown and control

First, differential Gene Expression analysis of RecQ1 vs CTL will be conducted first

d = DGEList(counts=data_matrix, group=samples$cell_type)
plotMDS(d, labels=rownames(samples),
 col = c("darkgreen","blue")[factor(samples$cell_type)], cex = 0.6, main = "MDS plot")

d <- estimateDisp(d, model_design)
fit <- glmQLFit(d, model_design)
qlf.RecQ1CTL <- glmQLFTest(fit, 
                        contrast = contrast_RecQ1CTL
                        )

Multiple hypothesis testing

For every gene, I correct them using Benjamini-Hochberg (Benjamini and Hochberg 1995), also known as fdr. I use this method because it is a powerful tool that decreases the false discovery rate and it is a common method for multiple hypothesis testing.

# adjust methods
qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL <- topTags(qlf.RecQ1CTL,
                           sort.by = "PValue",
                           n = nrow(normalized_count_data), 
                           adjust.method = "BH")

threshold

After that, I used cutoff of 0.05 for pvalue and fdr. This is because pvalue < 0.05 is statistically significant and it is a commonly used statistic threshold.

length(which(qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table$PValue < 0.05))
## [1] 553
length(which(qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table$FDR < 0.05))
## [1] 46

HeatMap

I use HeatMap to visualize the expression. From the result, we can see samples from each conditions cluster and the difference in expression is very apparent.

top_hits <- rownames(qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table)[
 qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table$PValue < 0.05]
heatmap_matrix_tophits <- t(
 scale(t(data_matrix[which(rownames(data_matrix) 
 %in% top_hits),])))
heatmap_matrix_tophits <- heatmap_matrix_tophits[,! colnames(heatmap_matrix_tophits) %in% c("Sample_siESR1_3",  "Sample_siESR1_1", "Sample_siESR1_2")]
if(min(heatmap_matrix_tophits) == 0){
  heatmap_col = colorRamp2(c( 0, max(heatmap_matrix_tophits)), 
                           c( "white", "red"))
} else {
  heatmap_col = colorRamp2(c(min(heatmap_matrix_tophits), 0, 
                             max(heatmap_matrix_tophits)), 
                           c("blue", "white", "red"))
}


ha_colours <- c("blue","red")
siCTLsiRecQ1classes <- unique(classes)
siCTLsiRecQ1classes <- siCTLsiRecQ1classes[siCTLsiRecQ1classes != "siESR1"]
names(ha_colours) <- unique(siCTLsiRecQ1classes)
ha <- HeatmapAnnotation(df=data.frame(
  type = classes[classes != "siESR1"]),
  col = list(type = ha_colours))

current_heatmap <- Heatmap(as.matrix(heatmap_matrix_tophits),
                           cluster_rows = TRUE,
                           cluster_columns = TRUE,
                           show_row_dend = TRUE,
                           show_column_dend = TRUE, 
                           col = heatmap_col,
                           show_column_names = TRUE, 
                           show_row_names = FALSE,
                           show_heatmap_legend = TRUE,
                           top_annotation = ha,
                           name = "Gene Expression for CTL vs RecQ1"
                          )
plot(current_heatmap)

Volcano Plot

I use volcano plot to visualize amount of differentially expressed genes. We can see that most of them are downregulated genes

volcano_data <- cbind(qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table$logFC, -log10(qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table$FDR))
colnames(volcano_data) <- c("logFC", "negative Log P-value")
degs <- qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table$FDR < 0.05 & abs(qlf_output_hits_RecQ1CTL$table$logFC) > 1
point.col <- ifelse(degs, "red", "black")
plot(volcano_data, 
     pch = 16, 
     col = point.col, 
     cex = 0.5,
     main = "Volcano Plot for Differentially Expressed Genes in RecQ1 vs CTL")

Thresholded over-representation analysis

For Thresholded over-representation analysis, I am going to use g:Profiler (Reimand et al. 2016). I use this tool because it is easy to use and incorporate many annotation data. I am going to use gprofiler2, the R client of gprofiler to conduct enrichment analysis.

The data source that I used are Reactome(Fabregat et al. 2018) and WikiPathways(Martens et al. 2021). I used these data source because I am looking for some specific pathways associated with ESR1, estrogen and breast cancer. Data source like GO:BP, GO:MF (Consortium 2004) contains molecular-level activities, which do not suits my needs. According to G:Profiler, the version of WikiPathways is 20211210 and Reactome is annotations: BioMart classes: 2022-1-3

Thresholded over-representation analysis for RecQ1 vs CTL

First, I will run g:Profiler for RecQ1 vs CTL with the all differentially expressed genes together and the up-regulated and down regulated differentially expressed genes separately

All differentially expressed genes together

Run gprofiler with parameters of correction method of FDR threshold of 0.05, Then I get 35 significant pathways

RecQ1CTL_gostres <- gost(query = RecQ1CTL_gene_list,
                organism = "hsapiens",
                correction_method = "fdr",
                user_threshold = 0.05,
                sources = c("REAC", "WP"))

RecQ1CTL_enrichment_result <- RecQ1CTL_gostres$result

Interpretation

This over-representation results support the conclusion discussed in the original paper. In the original paper, author states that RECQ1 regulates ERa signalling(Lu et al. 2021). Here, in my analysis, ESR-mediated signaling is down-regulated when RECQ1 is knocked down. Since ESR1 encodes ERa, we have evidence to say RECQ1 regulates ERa signalling. Whats more, author also points out that RECQ1 depletion causes downregulation of gene sets associated with estrogen response. In my analysis, Extra-nuclear estrogen signaling and Mammary gland development pathway is down-regulated when RECQ1 is knocked down. This provides another supporting evidence for relation between RECQ1 and estrogen. Also, author states that many genes downregulated in ESR1 knockdown are not downregulated in RECQ1 knockdown since RECQ1 could regulate only parts of ERa targets. This is also observed in my analysis. They share many of the pathways like Mammary gland development pathway, but ESR1 knockdown has far more downregulated genesets.

There are some evidence that support my results.First, we see Cholesterol biosynthesis and Cholesterol biosynthesis pathway is downregulated when ESR1 is knocked down. There are evidence (Klos et al. 2008) showing that variation of ESR1 influence HDL-cholesterol. Moreover, vitamin D receptoris upregulated when ESR1 is knocked down. There is also evidence that ESR1 is one of the regulators for vitamin D3 receptors[landel2016vitamin]. In their paper, they point out that ESR1 induce signal pathway of vitamin D supplementation against Alzheimers disease.
